===Etymology 2===
{{ja-kanjitab|むね|yomi=k}}
From {{inh|ja|ojp|-|sort=むね}}, from {{inh|ja|jpx-pro|*munai|sort=むね}}. The apophony is similar to the phonetic process observed in the shift from {{m|ja|神|tr=kamu|t=spirit, god|pos=older form used in compounds}} to {{m|ja|神|tr=kami|pos=newer form, used as a standalone noun}}; see [[WT:AJPX#Standalone forms and combining forms]].

Alternatively, may be a compound of {{compound|ja|sort=むね|身|tr1=mu|t1=body|根|tr2=ne|t2=root}}. Other theories have been suggested.<ref name="KDJ2O_chest">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten 2 Online|むね 【胸】|lid=200204167f7evJ8oO66L}}</ref>

The first edition of the Nihon Kokugo Daijiten says that this is cognate with {{m|ja|棟|tr=mune||main roofline, roof ridge}} and {{m|ja|宗}}, {{m|ja|旨|tr=mune||gist, main idea, primary part}}, from the underlying idea of ''central or main portion''.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref> However, the accent of {{m-self|ja|胸|tr=mune}} in the Heian period is <code>HL</code>,<ref name="KDJ2O_chest"/> while the accent of {{m|ja|棟|tr=mune}} is <code>HH</code>.<ref name="KDJ2O_ridge">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten 2 Online|むね 【棟】|lid=20020416ccc3N3pRGxi5}}</ref> This suggests that they may not be directly related.

Notably, {{m|ja|棟}} and {{m|ja|宗}} also have an older reading ''muna'' that is only used in compounds (for {{m|ja|宗}}, possibly only in place names). Meanwhile, {{m|ja|旨|tr=mune}} (Heian <code>HH</code><ref name="KDJ2O_gist">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten 2 Online|むね 【旨】|lid=200204167db9XoN90v59}}</ref>) appears in {{w|The Tale of Genji}} of {{circa2|1001-1004}}, and this reading is used as a standalone noun rather than in compounds. This is consistent with other nouns that have paired vowel forms, and suggests that ''muna'' is probably the original form, and that the compound derivation is a [[folk etymology]].

First attested in the ''{{w|Kojiki}}'' of 712 {{CE}}.<ref name="KDJ2O_chest"/>

